body:
https://lists.hyperledger.org/g/sawtooth/topic/28856556

check this link for the solution

> Thanks for the fixes. Your commit message needs a DCO line in the last line of your commit message, with your github account name and email address.
> Something like:
> 
> `Signed-off-by: rranjan3 <your.email.here@somewhere.com>`
> 
> (change `your.email.here@somewhere.com`). This is a legal requirement by The Linux Foundation and Hyperledger.
> See https://sawtooth.hyperledger.org/docs/core/releases/latest/community/contributing.html

Thanks Dan for the review. I have the DCO check passing. There are 3 separate commits(thought to separate out logical commits) all of which have the signoff.

> Could you improve the commit message for the "Fix list filter..." commit? It is unclear why you are making that change. It doesn't appear to be "broken", but a behavior change.

Thanks @peterschwarz for pointing it out. I have excluded that commit altogether. The intent in the commit was to fix the filters on all the pages that display a list of asset/agent/fish. But the fix was disabling the refresh also. Refresh is what causes the issue itself. Will take some more time to have a flawless fix to this and raise a separate PR later.
Please use standard Apache 2.0 text and/or SPDX
Please use standard Apache 2.0 text and/or SPDX
The goal is to get projects using the same license file.

@ryjones can you check why your PR isn't building? Someone mentioned seeing hangs when PRs aren't pushed from forks. 
Otherwise we're good to go from an approval perspective.

@dcmiddle it is failing due to a whitelist check - I guess I'm not whitelisted?

 > [Pipeline] readTrusted
 > Obtained bin/whitelist from aaa2a9a581c46e3851ba8ab9eaf10d6a536a77a0
 > [Pipeline] sh
 > [jenkins-Sawtooth-Hyperledger-sawtooth-supply-chain-ryjones-patch-1-1] Running shell script
 > \+ ./bin/whitelist  /etc/jenkins-authorized-builders
 > USAGE: ./bin/whitelist [user] [whitelist]
 > [Pipeline] }

@ryjones you are whitelisted. The issue here is that jenkins is not passing a user to the whitelist script. I have seen this happen before when pushing a branch directly to the repo instead of the usual fork and pull request.
please see #65
Should FLOAT be removed, or deprecated? How does this affect backward compatibility with Sawtooth 1.0?
Related RFC: https://github.com/Cargill/sawtooth-rfcs/blob/c003-supply-chain-expand-data-types/text/0000-supply-chain-expand-data-types.md
got it - didn't realize this was supply chain and not sawtooth-core.
As this and previous PR's have changed what enum values actually mean (as opposed to purely additive changes), there probably should be a PR to bump the `family_version` for this handler.
I agree, bumping up family_version is a good idea.
I have updated the `FAMILY_VERSION` to `'1.1'`.
Yes, full feature parity is the intent.

@dcmiddle An hour is definitely longer than I've experienced, but I can confirm that the Rust TP definitely takes longer to get running that the Python one was. I have front-loaded as much of that time into the build process as possible, so hopefully you can get `up` times of ~30 seconds once everything is built.
@askmish looks like you've got a merge conflict to resolve and then we can get this one merged.

The shell image contains a few extra dependencies for interacting with the sawtooth blockchain, and can be found here:
https://hub.docker.com/r/hyperledger/sawtooth-shell/
Thanks to @rkrish82  on chat for helping verify fix behind proxy.
I would approve this but can't as PR submitter; I do approve it.
Several of my line comments got hidden due to the file being updated in a future commit, but I think the comments are still valid
@peterschwarz I updated the rename commit. It takes into account container name collisions now as you described. Service names are not prefixed.
I think its good to verify first that you have the basic setup running and then throw the updates at it.
@dcmiddle @delventhalz
@delventhalz @dcmiddle
Suggest closing this PR as the docker-compose fix has already gone in elsewhere, and there doesn't seem to be any further conversation on the stack trace logging.

We should use supply-chain-tp or sawtooth-supply-chain-tp as the script name, for a couple reasons:

a) will make more sense in "ps" output
b) approach is compatible with projects with more than one transaction processor, for which this might serve as an example

Renamed to `supply_chain_tp`. Though I wonder now if the abbreviation "tp" is clear enough. Maybe "supply_chain_processor" would be more appropriate. In any case, merging it as is. Names can be nailed down later.
If I want to test this, is it recommended I use the sawtooth-core vagrant environment?
This not ready for testing, it gets us partially there.

Sorry, I meant the build commit specifically.
To know that this is doing the right thing are you building using dockers or vagrant or something else?

Cc: Middleton, Dan <dan.middleton@intel.com>; Comment <comment@noreply.github.com>

`./bin/protogen` is still generating protos for `families/supplychain`. Won't we be removing that code entirely? Track and Trade does not interface with it in any way.
I didn't remove any families/supplychain in this PR, but we can do that in the next one.

I tested build_all on my mac. I'm not sure if it requires running bin/build_all in sawtooth-core first.  There is a lot of work to get us to where we need to be here (reorganizing, etc.), so this was primarily focused on attempting to remove non-supply chain content.
Some Dockerfiles we use for CI tasks have been removed, but it's probably worthwhile to rewrite them rather than twist them around to be single purpose.
